				<td colspan="2"><span>I believe bards are going back to their original style in D&amp;D Lynnara, where they actually cast spells rarther than sang songs.  The more I read about EQ II the more I see I probably will be leaving EQ I for EQ II, unless Omens of War brings comparably unique features to EQ I.  
<br />

<br />
In any case, EQ II is dramatically different from EQ I.  One of the clearest differences, other than the graphics, is the fighting system as Talabus referred too.  I haven't played EQ II yet--and I am so looking forward to it--but the fact that the mobs will be intelligent, that is use AI (Artificial Intelligence), when encountering a player brings an entirely new feel to the game.  
<br />

<br />
There is so much intricacy and development being done in EQ II it makes sense that to attain 20 lvls of exp takes 100 hours or more of game play.  The lvl cap, as it stands right now, in EQ II is 50, which they plan to increase.  Personally, I feel it's the amount of time it would take to lvl up in EQ II which would cause me to leave EQ I, but we shall see.  I'd like to play both, simultaneously.  But as it seems presently EQ II is very much the better of EQ I, in terms of game play and prospects.
