				<td colspan="2"><span>steppy makes an excellent point but lets see if i can tell the future of EQ somewhat.
<br />

<br />
there was a thread going on over on the inny.com board concerning public raids and the such and it gave me some information that i had not really thought about but it gave me somewhat of an education concerning eq and eqII.
<br />

<br />
first, let me say that I used to say that i would never play EQII, even though i am scheduled for the next group of players that beta test EQII (i bought lords of everquest for christmas).  The current Everquest environment is making me prob change my mind.  Also, dont forget that the SOE pass is only 21.99 a month and will let you play both games and the ps2 online version of eq and all the other little games soe has online...which really isnt too bad.
<br />

<br />
back to the game environment... SOE has said that they will continue to support EQ, even including at least a couple more expansions.  This is fine but i feel that we have been seeing the decline of everquest, as a truly viable product, over the last couple of months.
<br />

<br />
we have seen a number of the large raiding guilds close their doors and go elsewhere or no longer be a raiding guild.  These guilds had already moved through pop and were banging their heads against GoD...with a great deal of frustration mind you.  Everquest is 5 years old..... a very old 5 years old.  We are seeing the rest of the high end raiding guilds scrambling for new guildies.  Unfortunately many of them will not back flag so apping toons are to group together in public raids to get those flags.  these public raids can only go so far.  In the meantime those high-end raiding guilds keep progressing.  The gap between the agressive raiding guilds and the casual guilds keeps growing.  The new guilds that are trying to build their ranks keep finding less and less new toons to help them in the high end PoP raids.  Alliances have been born and broken...
<br />

<br />
sooner or later, a new toon is going to get frustrated and not play Everquest anymore.  
<br />

<br />
Everquest will continue for quite some time as there are still many players that want to play casual...be with their friends and just have fun.  They are not concerned with the raid portion of the game.  The only problem there is that it is very hard to explore GoD without a group or raid from a guild that is time equipped.  OOW may very well be the same way.  I tend to get tired of doing the same thing day after day.  I like to see new content without joining an aggressive raid guild.  I dont have the time to put in so i will go nowhere but certain expansions and start new twinks....
<br />

<br />
What to do?
<br />

<br />
wellll... i can pretend to be an SCA member and live in EQ until they do close the doors....
<br />

<br />
Or i can play EQII, right when it comes out, enjoying new content and start at the same level playing field that everyone else is at....<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
what to do ... what to do...
<br />

<br />
guluvasea songweaver  lvl 58 bard
<br />
dekkon fuzzyfeet elder storm warden
